Introduction

This project aims to provide valuable information on the on-time performance of flights, which is used to measure quality of customer service by commercial transportation companies. We are measuring data only for the Pittsburgh. Our variables of interest are related to departure delay (DepDelay, DepDel15 and DepDel30), so we will only use the flights that are departing from Pittsburgh. We will be training our models on data from 2006 and testing it on data from 2016. In our analysis, we will use some features available in the data to generate others. We are especially interested in using delays of flights that were scheduled to depart two prior to a flight for which we will make the prediction.

The key predictions we will be considering in this project are : * Predicting the probability delay greater than 15 minutes and 30 minutes * Predicting the time of delay of flights using regression

Here are some exploratory statistics on our variables of interest and our data in general.

Step - 1: Feature Engineering

  1. If the flights are delayed within 2 hours before the departure of the respective flight
  • Proportion of the count of fligths delayed by 15 mins
  • Proportion of the count of fligths delayed by 30 mins
  • Average Delay

  1. If the flight with the same TailNum reaching Pittsburgh has faced a delay in arrival we collect its ArrDelay (again with a 2 hour window)

  2. If multiple flights with the same TailNum are departing from Pittsburgh, for the Nth trip that it makes, we will take the DepDelay of the (N-1)th flight’s delay.

## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam'

ggplot(intermediate_ADA_wFE_no_outliers, aes(x=prop_prev_delays_30_2hr, y=DepDelay)) + geom_point(colour="blue") + stat_smooth(colour="red") + xlab("Proportion of Flights Delayed by 30 minutes or more (in the last two hours)") + ylab("Departure Delay") + facet_wrap( ~ UniqueCarrier)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam'

After having engineered the feature of proportion of delayed flights two hours prior to a flight’s CRSDepTime we wanted to see the correlation between those proportions (both for flights delayed between 15 and 30 minutes, and those delayed more than 30 minutes) and our variable of interest DepDelay. For the sake of these charts we have filtered our the outliers which are delayed more than two hours (otherwise the data points get clumped at the bottom left corner of the graph). Furthermore, we are generating these graphs for each of the carriers to measure their performance to deal with “accumulating delay”.

b)Delay based on the Time of the Day

delays15 <- intermediate_ADA_wFE %>% filter(DepDelay > 15 & DepDelay < 30)
delays30 <- intermediate_ADA_wFE %>% filter(DepDelay > 30)
par(mfrow=c(1,3))
hist(intermediate_ADA_wFE$DepTime,xlab = "Hour of Day (0000-2300)", ylab = "Total Number of Flights", main = "Histogram of flight counts", ylim = c(0,6000), col = "cyan")
hist(delays15$DepTime, xlab = "Hour of Day (0000-2300)", ylab = "Number of Flights delayed by 15-30 minutes", main = "Histogram of delay counts (15-30)", ylim = c(0,1000), col = "steelblue")
hist(delays30$DepTime, xlab = "Hour of Day (0000-2300)", ylab = "Number of Flights delayed by 30+ minutes", main = "Histogram of delay counts (30+)", ylim = c(0,2000), col = "blue")

As we could see from the previous graph, delays tend to pile up. That is, a flight is affected by the delay of flights before it, and that flight in turn will affect the delay of the flights after it. In order to verify this, we have plotted three coloumn charts which show total number of flights across hour of day, along with number of flights delayed for 15-30 minutes, and more than 30 minutes also across hour of day. We can see that, more so for delays of more than 30 minutes, that the delays tend to pile up over the course of the day.

c)Delay based on the Seasons

require(gridExtra)
plot1 <- ggplot(delays15, aes(x=season, y=DepDel15)) + geom_col(fill="steelblue") + xlab("Season") + ylab("Number of Flights delayed by 15-30 minutes")
plot2 <- ggplot(delays30, aes(x=season, y=DepDel30)) + geom_col(fill="cyan") + xlab("Season") + ylab("Number of Flights delayed by 15-30 minutes")
grid.arrange(plot1, plot2, ncol=2)

seasonSummary15 <- intermediate_ADA_wFE %>% group_by(season) %>% summarise(meanDelay = mean(DepDelay))
seasonSummary15 <- data.frame(Season = seasonSummary15$season, AvgDelay = seasonSummary15$meanDelay)
plot3 <- ggplot(seasonSummary15, aes(x=Season, y=AvgDelay)) + geom_col(fill="blue") + xlab("Season") + ylab("Average departure delay")
grid.arrange(plot3, ncol=1)

We feel that seasonality affects flight demand patterns, which could in turn affect delays. The assumption is that fully booked or overbooked flights would have more delays. Another reason for bucketing flight dates into month was the assumption that weather patterns could affect flight delays, especially in the winter. However we see that our first assumption had merit as flights in the summer are delayed more often and flights in the winter are delayed the least often. We can see this pattern hold true with respect to average delays in the flights across seasons.

We ran a similar analysis on day of week and found that longer delays occured on Thursdays and Fridays. Flights on those days were also delayed more often. We have used these insights in creating a new variable where we flag all flights on Thursday or Friday as 1 and the rest as 0.

Separating the test and training data set for model validations. Using the same validation set across different models for a fair performance comparison.

################### test and train set separations ##############
#targetVariable Index
targetVariable <- which((names(ADS_fromPit_3) %in% c( "DepDelay")))
#predictor variables
ADS_fromPit_3_PV <- as.matrix(ADS_fromPit_3[,-targetVariable])
#target Variables
ADS_fromPit_3_TV <- ADS_fromPit_3[, targetVariable]
# test sample indeces
test <- sample(1:nrow(ADS_fromPit_3_PV), size = 5000)
ADS_fromPit_3_TV_class_15 <- ifelse(ADS_fromPit_3_TV > 15, 1, 0)
ADS_fromPit_3_TV_class_30 <- ifelse(ADS_fromPit_3_TV > 30, 1, 0)

Step - 3: Lasso

Lasso Regression as a classifier has been used to check for the linear hyperplane distinguisher between a flight being delayed or not. With the Lambda-plot against CV error, we take out the 1se Lambda value to use for classification of the test validation set. We see all the co-efficients at the 1se lambda value to be suppressed to 0. The classification results were favourable for the specificity region which is the costlier region in our scenario (classifying an On-Time flight as a Delayed one).

# Lasso with CV
ADS_fromPit_3_15.lasso.cv <- cv.glmnet(ADS_fromPit_3_PV[-test,], as.factor(ADS_fromPit_3_TV_class_15[-test]), nfolds = 20, family = "binomial")
ADS_fromPit_3_30.lasso.cv <- cv.glmnet(ADS_fromPit_3_PV[-test,], as.factor(ADS_fromPit_3_TV_class_30[-test]), nfolds = 20, family = "binomial")
# plotting the gauge the Lambda value
plot(ADS_fromPit_3_15.lasso.cv)

plot(ADS_fromPit_3_30.lasso.cv)

Step - 4: Single Tree

Single tree was deployed as a first step to understand the interaction between variables while accomplishing homogeneity by recursive partisioning of the data. We grow the tree to a large size and prune it back using 1se cp value. We again see that the model has a high specificity. Now that we have a single tree, we are pushing it towards a random forest to effectively reduce variance in our classification.

################ single tree #####################
ADS_fromPit_TreeData <- ADS_fromPit_3[ , which(!names(ADS_fromPit_3) %in% c(irr_vars))]
ADS_fromPit_TreeData$DepDelay15_target <- as.factor(ifelse(ADS_fromPit_TreeData$DepDelay > 15, "Yes", "No"))
ADS_fromPit_TreeData$DepDelay30_target <- as.factor(ifelse(ADS_fromPit_TreeData$DepDelay > 30, "Yes", "No"))
ADS_fromPit_TreeData_15 <- ADS_fromPit_TreeData[,which(!names(ADS_fromPit_TreeData) %in% c("DepDelay", "DepDelay30_target"))]
ADS_fromPit_TreeData_30 <- ADS_fromPit_TreeData[,which(!names(ADS_fromPit_TreeData) %in% c("DepDelay", "DepDelay15_target"))]

#str(ADS_fromPit_TreeData_15)

DepDel_DT <- rpart(data = ADS_fromPit_TreeData_15[test, ], formula = DepDelay15_target ~ . , method = "class", control = rpart.control(cp = 0.0001))
DepDel_DT_30 <- rpart(data = ADS_fromPit_TreeData_30[test, ], formula = DepDelay30_target ~ . , method = "class", control = rpart.control(cp = 0.0001))
plotcp(DepDel_DT)

plotcp(DepDel_DT_30)

#printcp(DepDel_DT)
#printcp(DepDel_DT_30)
#15 min model
cpTable <- as.data.frame(DepDel_DT$cptable)
cpTable$xse <- cpTable$xerror + cpTable$xstd
minCPxse <- cpTable$xse[which.min(cpTable$xerror)]
cpTableSubset <- cpTable[1:which.min(cpTable$xerror), ]
cp.1se <- cpTableSubset[which.min(abs(minCPxse - cpTableSubset$xerror)), "CP"]
cp.min <- DepDel_DT$cptable[which.min(DepDel_DT$cptable[,"xerror"]), "CP"]
#30 min model
cpTable_30 <- as.data.frame(DepDel_DT_30$cptable)
cpTable_30$xse <- cpTable_30$xerror + cpTable_30$xstd
minCPxse_30 <- cpTable_30$xse[which.min(cpTable_30$xerror)]
cpTableSubset_30 <- cpTable_30[1:which.min(cpTable_30$xerror), ]
cp.1se_30 <- cpTableSubset_30[which.min(abs(minCPxse_30 - cpTableSubset_30$xerror)), "CP"]
cp.min_30 <- DepDel_DT_30$cptable[which.min(DepDel_DT_30$cptable[,"xerror"]), "CP"]

# pruned tree
pruned_DepDel_DT <- prune(DepDel_DT, cp.1se)
pruned_DepDel_DT_30 <- prune(DepDel_DT_30, cp.1se_30)
rpart.plot(pruned_DepDel_DT, main = "Classification tree for Flight Delay (>15 mins) Prediction")

rpart.plot(pruned_DepDel_DT_30, main = "Classification tree for Flight Delay (>30 mins) Prediction")

#predict
pruned_DepDel_DT_pred <- predict(pruned_DepDel_DT, ADS_fromPit_TreeData_15[test,c(-ncol(ADS_fromPit_TreeData_15))], type="prob")
pruned_DepDel_DT_pred_30 <- predict(pruned_DepDel_DT_30, ADS_fromPit_TreeData_30[test,c(-ncol(ADS_fromPit_TreeData_30))], type="prob")

pruned_DT_15_preds <- ifelse(pruned_DepDel_DT_pred[,"Yes"] > 0.5, "Yes","No")

Step - 10: RF for 2016-17 data Classification and Prediction

Using the above built models, we classify and regress 2016-17 data for both >15min and >30 min category. The predictions are a little out of expectations. The models perform fairly in the region that is expected to be (specificity) but performed very poorly in the false negative regions. The mean absolute error of the Departure Delay is around ~9.5 mins for both the categories of >15 and >30 mins.

################ Classify and Regress on the 2016-17 data ###################

Flight delay warning system

The analytical component of a personalized flight delay warning system will use the data from our predictions. The delay warning system can be a mobile or web application. The prediction on the delay time made by our model can be used in our application. Using this predicted data, our application will be able to predict the time of delay for a particular flight enter by the user.

Example scenario: Use case 1: For booking a particular carrier, the user will be able to view the historical trend of flight delay. They will be able to compare different carriers to see their average flight delays, predicted flight delays for the chosen carriers based on multiple factors such as day of the week, month, holidays etc. Use case 2: Once a particular flight has been booked, on the day of the flight the user can be send live delay updates via text or email. Say, for instance if the flight is going to be delayed by more than 30 minutes, the user should be informed so they can plan their travel to the airport accordingly. In order to do this, however, it would be useful to have some weather data in both our training set (historical) and test set (live). If the flight is a connecting flight, (i.e. it will arrive at the airport before departing back to its origin or a third city) it will also be helpful to have live tracking information about the flight. Some information about the flight, such as size, engine capacity, seating capacity, will also help predict if the arriving flight will be delayed en route. All these new features can help give live predictions about departure delay.

Limitation of Data:

  1. The model does not take weather condition into consideration.
  • We can use the weather API to get the live updates
  • We will also need the historical weather data to teach our predictor variable.
  1. We will need live updates of the flights that are coming into Pittsburgh.
  • Model takes into consideration of the delay status of flights 2hour prior to the flight.
  • Give the live updates the predictor can be used to give the delay prediction
  1. The model does not take the plane size into consideration The data at hand does not consist this information. Solution: Use flightstats API, feed the tailnum to get the plane size
  • Given the plane size we can look at the how does it impact the flight delay.
  • If there is strong correlation between the plane and Departure Delay, we can use it to teach the classifier and the regression model to predict the delay using this information.
  • The combination of weather and plane size can be used to predict the delay. For e.g. if the weather is bad, there will be greater impact on small planes.

Comparison of 2006 and 2016 data for Pittsburgh Airport

  • There are 5 fewer carriers in 2016.
  • There are also fewer flights out of Pittsburgh in, down from approximately 46000 to 27000.
  • Mean delay has fallen from around 9 minutes to 6 minutes.
  • The proportion of flights which were delayed 15 minutes or more and 30 minutes or more have also dropped.
